:::summary
Plato's Allegory of the Cave, found in Book VII of the *Republic*, is the most famous philosophical illustration in Western history — a story of prisoners chained underground who mistake shadows for reality, one prisoner who escapes into the sunlight of true knowledge, and the philosopher's obligation to return and guide others toward truth. For Christians, the allegory resonates deeply with biblical themes of spiritual blindness and illumination, anticipating Paul's description of those who see "through a glass, darkly" until at last they see "face to face."
:::

